    "name": "COU1: Non-cannulated construct compression-bending prediction",
    "description": "FEA predicts construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw design under ASTM F1717 static compression-bending. Validated by direct comparison to bench testing (N=11 constructs across two laboratories). Model influence MEDIUM (testing confirms results); decision consequence MEDIUM (pedicle screw fracture leads to revision surgery, not death).",
    "intendedUse": "Demonstrate that the FEA modeling framework reproduces experimental compression-bending behavior of a non-cannulated pedicle screw construct within pre-established acceptance bounds (<10% QoI difference, E/uval < 1.96).",
    "modelInfluence": "Medium",
    "decisionConsequence": "Medium",
    "deviceClass": "Class II",
    "hasApplicabilityConstraint": {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/cou/cou1-noncannulated/applicability-constraint",
      "type": "ApplicabilityConstraint",
      "name": "Applicability constraint: non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw, ASTM F1717 static loading only",
      "description": "This credibility assessment applies exclusively to non-cannulated solid-core titanium-alloy (Ti-6Al-4V) pedicle screws with a 7.5 mm major diameter, evaluated under quasi-static ASTM F1717 compression-bending loading in a polyethylene block fixture. The assessment does NOT apply to cannulated variants, screws of differing diameter (outside 7.0–8.0 mm), dynamic fatigue loading, or in vivo loading conditions. Extrapolation to cervical or lumbar constructs using different rod diameters requires a separate COU."
    },
    "hasOperatingEnvelope": {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/cou/cou1-noncannulated/operating-envelope",
      "type": "OperatingEnvelope",
      "name": "Operating envelope: ASTM F1717 compression-bending test bounds",
      "description": "Displacement rate: 5 mm/min ± 0.5 mm/min. Applied compressive load range: 0–4500 N. Screw insertion angle: 0° ± 2° from fixture axis. Polyethylene block density: 0.32 g/cm³ ± 0.02 g/cm³ (ASTM F1839 Grade 15). Rod diameter: 5.5 mm cobalt-chrome. Ambient temperature: 23 °C ± 2 °C. Fixture span: 50 mm between screw centers. All FEA predictions are valid only within these bounds; extrapolation beyond ±15% of any bound requires re-validation."
    }
  },
  "hasSensitivityAnalysis": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/sensitivity/cou1-noncannulated-sa01",
    "type": "SensitivityAnalysis",
    "name": "One-at-a-time and variance-based sensitivity analysis for COU1 FEA model",
    "description": "A one-at-a-time (OAT) sensitivity study varied six input parameters — Ti-6Al-4V Young's modulus (±5%), screw-rod interface friction coefficient (0.1–0.4), polyethylene block modulus (±10%), applied load magnitude (±2%), mesh density (3 refinement levels), and screw insertion torque preload (0–4 Nm) — across the ASTM F1717 fixture geometry. Construct stiffness (primary QoI) showed greatest sensitivity to screw-rod friction coefficient (Sobol' first-order index S₁ = 0.41) and block modulus (S₁ = 0.29), while yield force was most sensitive to Ti-6Al-4V yield strength (S₁ = 0.55). Mesh density and insertion torque contributed less than 3% of total output variance individually. These findings informed the uncertainty quantification strategy: friction coefficient and block modulus were treated as epistemic uncertain inputs with uniform prior distributions, and their combined contribution was propagated through the model ensemble to produce the uval estimates reported in the validation results."
  },
